To find the union of two sets, D U E, we combine all the elements of both sets, but we only list each distinct element once, even if it appears in both sets.

Given:
D = {16, 19, 21}
E = {16, 18, 19, 20}

Therefore:
D U E = {16, 19, 21, 18, 20}

Note that 16 and 19 are in both D and E, but we only list these elements once in the union. We also order the elements from smallest to largest, although this is not strictly necessary when listing elements of a set.

Hence, the elements in the set D U E are {16, 18, 19, 20, 21}.

The set A' (also referred to as the complement of A) consists of all elements in the universal set U that are not in set A.

Given:
U = {20, 21, 22, 23, 24, 25, 26}
A = {23, 24, 25, 26}

The complement of A, denoted as A', includes all the members of the universal set U that are not in A. To find A', we simply list all the elements from U that are missing from A.

A' = {20, 21, 22}

So, the complement of A with respect to U contains the elements 20, 21, and 22, using the roster method (which means simply listing the elements of the set).

The symbol "‚à©" denotes the intersection of two sets, which is the set containing all elements that are common to both sets.

Given:
A = {1, 2, 3, 6}
B = {1, 6, 7}

To find the intersection A ‚à© B, we look for all elements that are in both set A and set B:

A ‚à© B = {1, 6}

So, the set A ‚à© B consists of the elements 1 and 6, which are common to both sets A and B.

The expression "(A U B)'" refers to the complement of the union of sets A and B. The complement of a set includes all the elements in the universal set U that are not in the set.

Given:
U = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7}
A = {2, 4, 6, 7}
B = {1, 4, 7}

First, we find the union of sets A and B:

A U B = {1, 2, 4, 6, 7}

The union contains all unique elements that are in either set A or set B, or in both.

Next, we find the complement of this union with respect to the universal set U:

(A U B)' = U - (A U B)

So, we subtract the elements of the union from U:

(A U B)' = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7} - {1, 2, 4, 6, 7}

(A U B)' = {3, 5}

The complement of the union of sets A and B consists of the elements {3, 5}, which are the only elements in the universal set U that are not in the union set A U B.
